Confluence bundles a copy of tomcat in its installer. Right now, administrators have to directly modify several files in a tomcat install, including the server.xml (or corresponding web-app-name.xml file), log4j.properties, catalina.properties, and any other configuration files read during service startup (e.g. setenv.sh in unix environments). None of these customizations are carried across to the next upgrade, which requires more manual intervention by the administrator installing the upgrade to resolve.

Confluence should provide a standard way of configuring these settings so that administrator customizations are cleanly separated from installation defaults, and so that we can detect if there are any conflicting changes during upgrades, and so that we can carry those customizations across to upgraded installs, and minimize the amount of work an administrator has to do for a typical upgrade.

